Yes — since you touched paths.py, initialize.py, server.py, status.py, deploy_server.py, deploy.py, and cli.py, I’d test in layers.

Start with syntax/import tests first, before running any real commands.

cd /path/to/aerolitctl/project
python3 -m compileall src

Then check for old/stale names from the rename:

grep -R "generated_bootstrap_vars_file" -n src || true
grep -R "aerolit_bootstrap_generated.yml" -n src || true
grep -R "bootstrap_repo_environment_playbook" -n src || true
grep -R "bootstrap_repo_environment.yml" -n src || true

Expected: ideally no matches for those old names, unless you intentionally left a compatibility comment somewhere.

Then check parser/help wiring:

python3 -m aerolitctl.cli --help
python3 -m aerolitctl.cli version
python3 -m aerolitctl.cli configure --help
python3 -m aerolitctl.cli configure init --help
python3 -m aerolitctl.cli configure server --help
python3 -m aerolitctl.cli status --help
python3 -m aerolitctl.cli deploy --help
python3 -m aerolitctl.cli deploy server --help

If you have the installed command available too, also run:

aerolitctl --help
aerolitctl version
aerolitctl status --help
aerolitctl deploy server --help

Then test that the configured path still works:

aerolitctl path show
aerolitctl bundle show
aerolitctl bundle validate

Now test init safely:

aerolitctl configure init --dry-run --non-interactive --verbose

Then test server config read/show:

aerolitctl configure server --show

Then test server config dry-run write path:

aerolitctl configure server --dry-run \
  --mode full \
  --interface ens160 \
  --server-ip 192.168.109.10 \
  --network 192.168.109.0/24 \
  --dhcp-start 192.168.109.100 \
  --dhcp-end 192.168.109.149 \
  --gateway none \
  --nfs-export-path /home/unix/bundle \
  --nfs-allow-clients 192.168.109.0/24 \
  --target-mount-path /home/unix/sysadmin

Then verify the renamed generated file path:

ls -l /opt/aerolit/aerolit-bundle/collections-hub/ansible/group_vars/all/
cat /opt/aerolit/aerolit-bundle/collections-hub/ansible/group_vars/all/aerolitctl_server_generated.yml

If that file name is correct and the contents look right, run:

aerolitctl status
aerolitctl status --verbose

The important things to check in status:

Generated server vars = aerolitctl_server_generated.yml
PXE playbook = pxe_server.yml
Controller playbook = ansible_controller.yml
No reference to bootstrap_repo_environment.yml
Next recommended command makes sense

Then test deploy server without changing anything:

aerolitctl deploy server --show
aerolitctl deploy server --dry-run
aerolitctl deploy server --dry-run --skip-interface
aerolitctl deploy server --dry-run --skip-nfs
aerolitctl deploy server --dry-run --skip-pxe
aerolitctl deploy server --dry-run --skip-controller

Also test the split modes, because these catch a lot of wiring mistakes:

aerolitctl configure server --dry-run --mode pxe --show
aerolitctl configure server --dry-run --mode controller --show
aerolitctl configure server --dry-run --mode full --show

If you have deploy pxe and deploy ansible parser stubs already started, test only help for now:

aerolitctl deploy pxe --help
aerolitctl deploy ansible --help

If they don’t exist yet, it should fail cleanly and that’s fine.

Then run Git checks:

git diff --check
git status
git diff -- src/aerolitctl/paths.py
git diff -- src/aerolitctl/initialize.py
git diff -- src/aerolitctl/server.py
git diff -- src/aerolitctl/status.py
git diff -- src/aerolitctl/deploy_server.py
git diff -- src/aerolitctl/deploy.py
git diff -- src/aerolitctl/cli.py

The highest-value final smoke test is this sequence:

aerolitctl path show
aerolitctl bundle validate
aerolitctl configure server --show
aerolitctl status
aerolitctl deploy server --show
aerolitctl deploy server --dry-run

Do not run non-dry-run aerolitctl deploy server yet until those all pass cleanly and the generated vars file name/content looks exactly right.